ve agents. Drawing on and modifying the theories of John Rawls, Michael Walzer, Ronald Dworkin, Joseph Raz, Amartya Sen, and others, Johnston explains how this purpose can be realized in a world in which human beings hold fundamentally different conceptions of the ends of life. His humanist liberalism responds constructively to feminist, neo-Marxist, and other criticisms while remaining faithful to the core values of the liberal tradition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aLiberalism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140082151840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400821518423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400821518.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK